		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName> <date>Dec 6. 1852</date></p>
			<p><addressee>Rev Dr Leeser</addressee> Ed of the Occident</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">Dear Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)">Enclosed find<lb/> a reply from <persName>Rev C. D Oliver</persName>&#44; of <placeName>Mont&#45;<lb/>gomery Ala</placeName> to the letter of <persName>Rev E Marcus&#45;<lb/>sohn</persName> to the Editor of the Jewish Chronicle <date>Sept<lb/> 16&#44; 1852</date> as per <date>Oct.</date> Occident which you will oblige the<lb/> friends in <placeName>Montgomery</placeName> by publishing<lb/> And allow me to say in this con&#45;<lb/>nection&#44; that whatever may have<lb/> been <persName>Mr Marcussohn&#39;s</persName> motives&#44; he<lb/> carried his self deception if we admit that<lb/> he was self&#45;deceived to a remarkable extent<lb/> if we do not admit this&#44; then he carried<lb/> out his deception of others to the same extent.<lb/> For the alternative present itself&#44; that either<lb/> he was self&#45;deceived&#44; &#40;this he denies&#41; or he was deceiving others. For after he made<lb/> his profession of belief in the doctrines<lb/> of Christianity&#44; to Christian parties in <placeName>Mont<lb/>gomery</placeName>&#44; we were solicited to do something<lb/> to aid him in a pecuniary way. We<lb/> proposed to the friends that if they could<lb/> recommend him to let him to work as<lb/> a missionary to the Jews&#44; under our care<lb/> They recommended him. We made a proposal</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>to employ him&#44; as He accepted it&#44; and soon<lb/> after entered the field under the supervision<lb/> of our missionary at <placeName>Charleston</placeName>. As evi&#45;<lb/>dence of the latter fact our Treasurer has<lb/> settes<add>&#63;</add> receipt for money received by him for his<lb/> labors&#44; as a missionary&#44; to convert the Jews to<lb/> Christianity. Of course we were gratified<lb/> at the conversion to our faith of a man<lb/> of <persName>Mr Marcussohn&#39;s</persName> standing. We believed<lb/> him sincere&#44; and acted accordingly<lb/> It was certainly a thing of his own seeking<lb/> not ours. Allow us to say Mr Editor<lb/> that our principle of action in our work<lb/> of converting Israelites to our faith is<lb/> based upon the firm conviction that<lb/> Christianity as found in the new Testament<lb/> is the religion of <persName>Abraham</persName> <persName>Isaac</persName> &#38; <persName>Jacob</persName><lb/> and that Judaism&#44; as now held&#44; is not&#44; hence<lb/> our anxiety respecting the salvation of Israel<lb/>ites. But our principles will not permit<lb/> us to make mere proselytes. We want only<lb/> those who thoroughly believe in intellect<lb/> and heart in the Christian religion&#44; to join us<lb/> To make such converts is our aim. We<lb/> supposed <persName>Mr Marcussohn</persName> such an one<lb/> and called him ours Now <persName>Mr M.</persName> finds<lb/> he was mistaken. Of course we are not about<lb/> condemning him for returning to his former faith<lb/> but he ought to have told the truth as it is</p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p>and I am sure all parties would have<lb/> respected him more highly. We have<lb/> no disposition to injure <persName>Mr M.</persName> No. No<lb/> God <sic>furbid</sic> but no one can blame<lb/> us for setting public opinion right as<lb/> to the course pursued by certain respecta&#45;<lb/>ble clergymen whose statement respecting<lb/> <persName>Mr M&#39;s</persName> conversion have been so flatly<lb/> denied by him</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">I remain as ever</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)">Truly Yours</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">R McGregor</persName> Secy</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)">ASMC Jews</p>
          
        </body>
